Description: Soft "fluffy" looking mud, brittle stars, microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s, burrows, tracks
General Public Description: On the soft "fluffy" mud, tracks and burrowing prints of common seafloor organisms such as brittle stars and molluscs can be seen.

Description: Soft "fluffy" looking mud, microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s, burrows, tracks, octopus
General Public Description: An octopus lies on soft-sediment near large fluffy microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s, and small tracks and burrowing marks of other sea creatures.

Description: Soft "fluffy" looking mud, microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s, burrows, tracks, fish, macroalgae, cushion star fish, hermit crab
General Public Description: Large microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s cover most of the seafloor. Starfish, hermit crabs and small invertebrate tracks and burrows can be seen.

Description: Rocky substrate, anemones, fish, eleven arm starfish, macroalgae, blue cod, starfish, sponges, urchins
General Public Description: White sea anenomes are seen spread over rocky surfaces, also attached is an eleven-armed starfish, macroalgae, bright sponges and urchins.

Description: Urchins, blue cod, sea cucumbers, macroalgae, eleven arm starfish, brittle stars, shell hash, microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s, tracks
General Public Description: Blue cod swim over the shell hash, sea urchins and microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s which dominate the seafloor, while the odd eleven-armed starfish, sea cucumbers, brittlestars and sponges are present on top.

Description: Urchins, blue cod, sea cucumbers, macroalgae, eleven arm starfish,  shell hash, horse mussel, sponges
General Public Description: Blue cod is seen grazing over shell hash and eleven-armed starfish. Small abundances of macroalgae is surrounded by a large amount of sea urchins and the occassional sea slug.

Description: Soft "fluffy" looking mud, microphytobenthos (microscopic algae), tracks, scallops, macroalgae
General Public Description: Large areas of semi-green mats of microphytobenthos (microscopic algae) cover the soft mud floor. Tracks of different neighbouring species line the seafloor where small amounts of scollaps lie.

Description: Tube worms, urchins, blue cod, spotty, sea cucumbers, shell hash
General Public Description: There are dense quantities of tube worms lying in the sand or attached to rocks next to urchins and sea cucumbers; cautiously watching are spotty fish and blue cod.

Description: Sponges, brittle star, horse mussel, shell rubble, sea cucumbers, cushion stars, blue cod, tube worms
General Public Description: Shell rubble covers the seafloor whilst large horse mussels, tube worms, brittle stars and cushion stars attempt to find space. Dark sponges can also be seen

Description: Soft sediment , sea slug, sponges, turret shells, sea cucumber, urchins, sea snails
General Public Description: Bright orange sponges are spotted peaking through the soft sediment, whilst sea slugs, sea cucumbers, turret shells, urchins and sea snails lie close.

Description: Soft sediment , eleven arm starfish, sponges, urchins, burrows, horse mussels, turret shells
General Public Description: Bright orange sponges peak through the soft sediment whilst dense patches of tube worms are close by. The occassional eleven-armed starfish, sea urchins, horse mussels and turret shells is also present.

Description: Soft muddy sediment, many burrows, urchins
General Public Description: Soft sediment with the occassional urchin with little burrows of organisms; not much life can be seen here on the surface.

Description: Soft mud, burrows, fish, tube worms
General Public Description: Soft sediment with different sized burrows and tube worms

Description: Blue cod, Ancorinid sponge, spotties, tube worms, eleven arm starfish, tube worms, turret shells, tunicates, sea cucumbers
General Public Description: Blue cod and spotty fish glide over the rocky surfaces, where sponges, tube worms and sea cucumbers can be seen over multiple turret shells. A few sea squirts are also present.

Description: Soft muddy sediment, burrows, anemone, tube worms
General Public Description: Soft muddy sediment shows distinct burrow patterns and tube worms.

Description: Soft muddy sediment, burrows, tracks, microphytobenthos (microscopic algae), scallop, eleven arm starfish, fish
General Public Description: Dark microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s, tracks and burrows cover the soft muddy sediment where you can see scallops, eleven-armed starfish and different types of fish.
A large dark brittle star lies on the soft seafloor amongst some algae.
Macroalgae uses their holdfasts to anchor themselves to the seafloor. Blue cod and starfish can also be found within the algae.

Description: Anemone, horse mussels, macroalgae, sea cucumber
General Public Description: Large horse mussels and a sea cucumber on the seafloor, with some scattered ulva (green algae).

Description: Tarakihi, blue cod, urchins, macroalgae, spotty
General Public Description: Blue cod dash across the camera, whilst next to some macroalgae a school of tarakihi and a lone spotty swim. On a rocky outcrop with some macroalgae, a sea urchin hangs out.
Scallop shells can be seen on the seafloor. These animals eat particles suspended in the water.
Microphytobenthos (microscopic algae) on the seafloor are disturbed by other seafloor-dwelling animals, leaving a criss-cross pattern of tracks.

Description: Sponges, spotty, sea cucumber, urchins, tube worms, tunicates, blue cod
General Public Description: A school of spotty fish dash around. Under a passing blue cod, sea cucumbers (dark, sausage-looking creatures, like ocean vacuums), tube worms, sea urchins and sea squirts amongst sponges are visible.

Description: Burrows, fish, tunicates, sponges, scallop, tube worms, horse mussels, brittle stars
General Public Description: Scallops, sea urchins and horse mussels scatter tje deafloor. A brittle star also roams this soft seafloor. Below them are the burrows of the animals living below the sediment surface, creating a three-dimensional seafloor. Sponges and sea squirts are also present.

Description: Scallops, sponges, horse mussels, brittle star, microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s, tracks, burrows,
General Public Description: The pearl coloured shells of scallops lie on this seafloor. Behind some horse mussels, a brittle star hangs out. Also visible are sea sponges, microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s and the tracks of seafloor dwelling creatures.

Description: Scallops, horse mussels, burrows, tracks, microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s, sponges, brittle star, urchins, eleven arm starfish, blue cod, sea cucumbers, spotty
General Public Description: Scallops are visible on the soft surface. Horse mussels tower over microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s marked with the borrows and tracks of sea organisms, like a highway. Echinoderms (brittle star, sea cucumbers, urchins,  eleven-armed starfish) hang out with sponges. Spotty and blue cod fish glide by.

Description: Horse mussels, tube worms, brittle star, cushion star, urchins, sea cucumber, scallops
General Public Description: Large horse mussel shells protrude from the seafloor. Amongst them, a brittle star's snake-like arms are visible. Tube worms, cushion stars and the dark elongated shapes of sea cucumber can be seen.  Scallops and urchins stand out.

Description: Urchins, cushion star, eleven arm starfish, sea cucumber,
General Public Description: The soft sandy floor is alive with activity. A sea cucumber lies just above a cushion sea star, whilst in the background, eleven-armed starfish explore their surroundings with their tube feet. The spikey silhouette of sea urchins are also discernible.

Description: Eleven arm starfish, horse mussel, microphytobenthos (microscopic algae), tracks, sponges, turret shell, urchins, blue cod,
General Public Description: An eleven-armed starfish sits on a horse mussel. The tracks of animals are visible amongst the microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)ts and sponges on the soft floor. A turret shell (sea snail) and sea urchins also inhabit this floor surface, whilst a blue cod swims above them.
Tube worms like those seen here play an incredibly important role in soft seabed ecology, moving water and sediment through the sediment.

Description: Blue cod, sea cucumbers, tube worms, fish, eleven arm starfish, horse mussel
General Public Description: Blue cod fish swim above a seafloor dotted with sea cucumbers and tube worms. We can see an eleven-armed starfish and a horse mussel also call this patch of soft seafloor home.

Description: Eleven arm starfish, sea cucumber, blue cod, spotty, brittle star
General Public Description: Spotty fish swim next to blue cod. Echinoderm members  (a brittle star, eleven-armed starfish and sea cucumbers) hang out.

Description: microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s, tracks, urchins, eleven arm starfish, horse mussel, blue cod
General Public Description: Highway-like tracks created by sea creatures are highlighted amongst microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s.  An eleven-armed starfish, horse mussels, sea urchins and a cushion star are also present. A blue cod dashes across the camera.

Description: Urchins, sea cucumbers, sponges, blue cod, spotty, eleven arm starfish, octopus
General Public Description: Sea urchins dot the seafloor alongside sea cucumbers. Sponges and a starfish lie on the shell-littered sandy surface.  Predatory blue cod, spotty fish and an octopus are here too.

Description: Urchins, sea cucumbers, tube worms, anemones, tunicates, sponges
General Public Description: A living seafloor carpeted with sea squirts, tube worms, sponges and anemones. Sea urchins and cucumbers are also discernible.

Description: Urchins, horse mussels, tube worm, starfish, carpet shark, gurnard, eagle rays,
General Public Description: The silhouettes of horse mussels protrude out of the sand. Tube worms, starfishs, and urchins also dwell on this seafloor. The predators carpet shark, eagle rays and gurnard are also present.

Description: Scallops, tubeworms, hermit crabs, spotty, blue cod, tracks, microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s, eleven arm starfish, horse mussels, brittle stars
General Public Description: Hermit crabs move amongst scallop shells, tube worms and microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s. A spotty fish swims above animal tracks. Blue cod swim above eleven-armed starfish. Also spotted are brittle stars and horse mussels.
The pale shape of a starfish stands out on a rock. Spotty and blue cod fish hang around.

Description: Horse mussel, brittle star, cushion star, gurnard, sea cucumber, spotty, eleven arm starfish
General Public Description: A brittle star, eleven-armed starfish, sea cucumber and cushion star can be seen. A gurnard fish dashes away from the camera, whilst some spotty fish hang around some horse mussels.

Description: Horse mussel, cushion star, brittle star
General Public Description: Sitting on a horse mussel is a cushion star, while below it the snake-like arms of a brittle star are visible.

Description: Eleven arm starfish, horse mussel, urchins, sponges, blue cod, leather jacket, tube worms, sea cucumber, brittle star
General Public Description: Horse mussels jut out of the sand next to an eleven-armed starfish. Filter-feeding sponges and urchins are discernible, while a curious leather jacket and a blue cod swim above tube worms. A sea cucumber and brittle star stand out.

Description: Shell hash, rock fragments, silty bottom, urchin
General Public Description: This seafloor is composed of shell hash, rock fragments and silt. A sea urchin sits amongst the rocks.

Description: Blue cod, brittle star, sea cucumber
General Public Description: A blue cod dashes past the camera. The dark forms of a brittle star and sea cucumber stand out

Description: Horse mussel, brittle star, eleven arm starfish, blue cod
General Public Description: A group of horse mussels stick out like teeth to filter feed. Brittle stars can be seen amongst the mussels. Eleven-armed starfish are visible, while a blue cod swims above the soft surface.
Eleven-armed starfish explore their surroundings on their tube feet, while blue cod cruise above them.

Description: Burrows, eleven arm starfish, horse mussel
General Public Description: In the soft substrate, sea-creature burrows leave gaping holes. Eleven-armed starfish and horse mussels live here.

Description: Urchin, horse mussels, blue cod, shell hash
General Public Description: A sea urchin sits on the bottom, while a curious blue cod swims close to the camera. A filter-feeding horse mussel sticks out.

Description: Urchin, horse mussels (dead & alive), cushion star, microphyto benthos (MPB), tracks
General Public Description: A sea urchin sits not too far away from a dead horse mussel. A cushion star and a living horse mussel stand out against microphytobenthos (microscopic algae) on the seafloor covered with animal tracks.
Blue cod dash around Galeolaria, a species of fanworm.
A curious leatherjacket fish pokes around. Below it lie eleven-armed starfish.
Next to a sea urchin lies a golf ball sponge. Turret shells carpet this soft sediment seafloor.

Description: brittlestar, horse mussels, blue cod, burrows
General Public Description: Brittle stars and horse mussels can be seen. A blue cod fish swims past. Burrows are evident on the soft surface.

Description: Galeolaria, blue cod, microphyto benthos (MPB) tracks
General Public Description: Blue cod and a spotty fish swim amongst Galeolaria fanworms. A carpet of microphytobenthos (microscopic algae) is criss-crossed with the tracks of sea creatures.

Description: Sponges, spottys, reef, eleven arm starfish, MPB tracks, blue cod
General Public Description: Sponges filter the water. Some cruising spotty fish are visible. A blue cod swims above the tracks through the microphytobenthos (microscopic algae). An eleven-armed starfish clings to the reef.
Mats of microphytobenthos (microscopic algae) are punctured by the burrows of seafloor-dwelling creatures.

Description: Dogfish shark, brittle stars, opal fish, flounder, octopus
General Public Description: Large animals like the dogfish, brittle star, opal fish, flounder and octopus in this video play an important interacting ecological role in soft seafloors, disturbing the sediment and the algae community and predating on other animals.
A flounder and a brittle star lie side by side.

Description: Leather jackets, cod, kelp, brittle stars
General Public Description: Leatherjackets and blue cod fish glide above kelp clinging to the bottom. Brittle stars spread their arms out.
The microphytobenthos (microscopic algae) covered surface is interrupted by sea urchins and burrowing animals.
Amongst a thick mat of algae, a horse mussel is visible. Horse mussels and a sea urchin also inhabit a sandy surface.

Description: Algae, horse mussels, tube worms, flounder
General Public Description: Clumps of algae rest on the soft sediment. Horse mussels and tube worms create a three-dimensional floor surface. A flounder glides just above the seafloor.

Description: Urchins, algae, eleven arm starfish, cushion stars, turret shells,
General Public Description: Algae and sea urchins  dot the surface. An eleven-armed starfish explores the sandy surface not too far away from cushion stars. Turret shells are visible.

Description: Trigger fish, algae, horse mussels, sea cucumbers, turret shells, spotty, worm tubes
General Public Description: Spotty fish swim away. Two curious leatherjacket fish stay in view. Horse mussels and tube worms poke out of the sandy floor. Sea cucumbers blob on the sandy floor covered with turret shells.
An algae-covered horse mussel protrudes out of the sandy floor, where next to it, worm tubes are visible.

Description: Amazing horse mussel patch! Turret shells, spottys, scallops, sponges
General Public Description: Spotty fish glide amongst a beautiful horse mussel patch. This patch is also home to scallops, sponges and turret shells (sea snail).
A reef covered in Galeolaria (fan worms). Sea anemones and bryozoans add to the biodiversity of this reef.
This seafloor is alive with the activity of burrowing animals and filtering horse mussels.

Patches of tube worms can impact the flow of water over the surface of a soft sediment bed. This has important consequences for seafloor processes involving nutrient and sediment movement between the seafloor and the water column above it.

Description: Banded wrasse, sponges, spottys, urchins, eleven arm starfish, turret shells, blue cod, microphytobenthos (microscopic algae), burrows
General Public Description: Banded wrasse, blue cod, and spotty fish swim close the surface of this soft seafloor. Predatory eleven-armed starfish and herbivororous sea urchins also disturb the sediment surface where turret shells are also found. Sponges filter the water for small food particles. The pockmarks of burrowing animals disturb microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s, creating a three dimensional surface.

Description: Blue cod, tube worm, spotty , sponge, eleven arm starfish
General Public Description: Blue cod and spotty fish impact seafloor nutrient recycling with their predatation and excretion. Protruding tube worms and sponges are also a part of the biodiversity that impacts soft-sediment processes. Eleven-armed starfish move about.

Description: Blue cod, cushion stars, burrows, spottys, eleven arm starfish, leather jacket, brittle stars, microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)
General Public Description: Spotty, blue cod, leatherjacket fish can be seen. Eleven-armed starfish, cushion stars and brittle stars roam the seafloor, disturbing the sediment. microphytobenthos (microscopic algae) in mats can excrete a sticky mucous, sticking together sand particles. Burrowing animals disturb these mats.

Description: Brittle stars, blue cod, ulva, turret shells, sea cucumber, spottys, leather jacket
General Public Description: Echinoderms in this video are sea cucumbers and brittle stars. Blue cod, spotty and leatherjacket fish also inhabit this territory. Turret shells and ulva (green algae) can also be seen.
Blue cod seen here, endemic to New Zealand, are predators that impact nutrient imput in soft sediment habitats.

Description: Spottys, ulva, blue cod, urchins, tube worms, sponges, sea cucumbers, octopus
General Public Description: Ulva (green algae) stand out in the blue amongst blue cod and spotty fish. Urchins, tube worms, sea cucumbers and sponges dwell on this seafloor. An octopus disturbs the sediment with its movement.

Description: Urchins, brittle stars, ulva, sea cucumbers, blue cod, eleven arm starfish, sea horse, sponges, cushion stars, burrows, microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)
General Public Description: Soft seafloors are biologically diverse. Amongst microphytobenthos (microscopic algae) and blue cod we see sea urchins, eleven-armed starfish, cushion stars, sea cucumbers, and brittle stars. A seahorse is briefly seen. Sponges protrude from the seafloor. Animal burrows point to the hidden bustle of activity below the sediment surface, a surface covered in microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s.

Description: Blue cod, sea cucumber, eleven arm starfish, brittle stars
General Public Description: Curious predatory blue cod dwell on the seafloor.  Brittle stars, an eleven-armed starfish and sea cucumber (all echinoderms) also disturb the sand with their movement and feeding. Their activity can impact the flux of nutrients across the seafloor-water column boundary.

Description: Finger sponges, urchins, turret shells, brachiopods, brittle star, burrows
General Public Description: Finger sponges stick out of the sediment. Brachiopods (shelled animals) also protrude from the sand, while an urchin grazes near by. The spindly arms of a brittle star are discernible. Burrowing animals impact the exchange of sediment and nutrient particles in seafloor habitats as they dig.

Description: Blue cod, tube worms, ulva, sea cucumber, eleven arm starfish, turret shells
General Public Description: Tube worms create a three-dimensional surface, where ulva (green algae) stand out. Above them, blue cod swim. An eleven-armed starfish and sea cucumber take refuge. Turret shells litter the sand.

Description: Sea cucumbers, starfish, blue cod, eleven arm starfish, sponges, urchins, tarakihi, turret shells
General Public Description: Sea cucumbers (dark and sausage-like) can be desposit feeders, ingesting particles on the seafloor. Among them sits an eleven-armed starfish. Sponges and sea urchins are visible, and above them swim blue cod and takakihi fish. Turret shells litter the seafloor.

Description: Sea cucumbers, turret shells, brittle stars, urchins, sponges,
General Public Description: Sea cucumbers are also known as holothurians. Next to them are brittle stars with long spindly arms. Urchins, sponges and turret shells are also visible on the seafloor.

Description: Sea cucumbers, urchins, blue cod, spottys, tarakihi, sponges, opal fish, tube worms
General Public Description: Urchins and sea cucumbers roam the rocks and sand. Blue cod and schools of spotty and tarakihi swim. A brittle star takes refuge at the base of a sponge. An opal fish follows the camera lights. Tube worms protrude from the sand - they can impact ecological processes both above and below the surface of the seafloor.

Description: Brittle stars, tracks, microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s, urchins, opal fish, sponges, hermit crab
General Public Description: Amongst microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)ts criss-crossed with the tracks of epifauna (animals living on the seafloor surface), a brittle star and sea urchin are visibile. An opal fish dashes away from the camera. A hermit crab slowly crawls away.

Description: Banded wrasse, marble fish, sea cucumbers, anemones, trevally, eleven arm starfish, urchins, sponges, brittle stars
General Public Description: Banded wrasse and marble fish cruise above sea cucumbers and sea urchins. Trevally swim above sea anemones. Eleven-armed starfish and brittle stars rest near sponges.
An orange brittle star rests near a turret shell.

Description: Anemones, brittle stars, urchins, blue cod, sponges, ulva, turret shells, carpet shark, sea cucumber
General Public Description: The striking shapes of sea anemones and brittle stars stand out. Sea cucumbers and urchins move across the floor. Blue cod dash about. A carpet shark camouflages in the sand amongst ulva and turret shells.

Description: Urchins, blue cod, sea cucumber, brittle stars, turret shells, eleven arm starfish, sponges, octopus
General Public Description: Brittle stars, eleven-armed starfish, urchins and sea cucumbers roam about this seafloor littered with some turret shells. A curious octopus makes a grab for the camera weight. Sponges feed on particles suspended in the water.

Description: Tarakihi, blue cod, eleven arm starfish, brittle star, ulva
General Public Description: A tarakihi fish crosses the camera. Brittle stars rest among ulva (green algae), while blue cod investigate above. A lone eleven-armed starfish rests on the sand.

Description: Sea cucumbers, sponges, burrows, microphytobenthos (microscopic algae), tracks, anemones, macroalgae, hermit crab, eleven arm starfish
General Public Description: microphytobenthos (microscopic algae) (algae) excrete a sticky mucous and form mats. This living mat is disturbed by tracks and borrows. Sea anemones stand out starkly amongst a clump of macroalgae. An eleven-armed starfish shelters in a sandpit. A hermit crab makes a home in a turret shell. The dark shape of a sea cucmber stands out against the green.

Description: Ditom mats, tracks, burrows, cushion star, eleven arm starfish, urchins, dogshark
General Public Description: microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s (patterned here with tracks and burrows) are part of the microphyotobenthos (MPB) community. MPB provide an important food source for seafloor dwelling animals, as it is rich in protein. This energy supports higher trophic levels: a dogfish  crosses the camera.  Eleven-armed starfish, cushion stars and sea urchins are present here.
An eleven-armed starfish uses its tube feet to move about and explore its surroundings, searching for food.

Description: Cushion stars, microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s, burrows, sea cucumbers, sea snails
General Public Description: microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s provide important ecosystem functions such as primary productivity on the seafloor and sediment stability. Amongst animal burrows cushion stars, sea snails (sea snails) and sea cucumbers are visible.
A starfish is visible. A gurnard fish dashes away.

Description: Sea cucumbers, spotty, blue cod, urchins, eleven arm starfish, cushion stars
General Public Description: Sea cucumbers travel this seafloor. Sea urchins, eleven-armed starfish, and cushion stars also roam this seafloor. A spotty and blue cod fish cross the camera.
Shells on the sandy surface provide habitat for a cushion star.

Description: Fish, sea cucumbers, burrows, sponges, tracks, microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s, eleven arm starfish, brittle stars
General Public Description: Fish, sponges, sea cucumbers, eleven-armed starfish and brittle stars are a part of the visible biodiversity on this seafloor. Tracks are visible. Burrows indicate the activity taking place below the sediment.

Biogenic habitats, such as this one created by tubeworms, can impact water flow and soft-sediment processes like sediment stability and the settlement of other animals. The dark silhouette of a sea cucmber stands out in the middle.

Description: Sea cucumber, urchins, spotty, tube worms
General Public Description: Spotty fish swim above sea urchins, a sea cucumber and tube worms.

Description: microphytobenthos (microscopic algae), tube worm case, soft mud
General Public Description: On this soft mud floor microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s, a microbial community, excrete a sticky substance that can impact proccesses like nutrient exchange. A tube worm case stands out in the centre.
Brittle stars and sea urchins are among the animals that travel across the seafloor in search of food.
Cushion stars and sea urchins travel the seafloor in search of food on their tube feet.

Description: Blue cod, spotty, eleven arm starfish, sea cucumber, tarakihi
General Public Description: Spotty, blue cod and tarakihi fish play important predatory roles. Eleven-armed starfish and sea cucumbers roam the seafloor.
Shells provide habitat for seafloor creatures. Structural habitats like this are important for biodiversity.
A sea urchin sits close to tube worms. Though animals such as these can be described as having 'alien qualities,' they have inhabited earth for longer than humans.
Turret shells and a brittle stars are visible. Above them, spotty fish swim.
Eleven-armed starfish walk on the seafloor using their many tiny tube feet. These starfish are part of soft-sediment processes like consuming prey and providing organic matter for breakdown.

A muddy bottom with pits. The few first centemetres underneath the surface of soft seafloors can be a home for 'alien-like' animals. Moving in their tunnels, animals living within the sediment can affect the flow of oxygen and organic material from the surface to some depth within the mud. Too much mud however, can choke these animals.
The pale shape of a starfish stands out amongst the algae on a soft seafloor. Cushion stars are also visible.
Turret shells (visible here) can be either predators or algae grazers depending on their species. A sponge can also be seen here.
Amongst a bed of shells, turret shells are easily recognised by their conical shape. Importantly, the process of shell formation contributes to many ecosystem functions like carbon sequestration.

Description: Sponges, horse mussel shell, tube worm
General Public Description: The distinct shapes of a horse mussel shell and tube worm can be seen here. Sponges (yellow, round in this image) filter the water for food particles.

Description: Tube worms, urchin covered in shell fragments
General Public Description: Tube worms protrude from the seafloor. A sea urchin has covered itself in shell fragments as camouflage. There are different reasons suggested for covering behaviour in urchin species including protection from predators and UV light

Description: Blue cod, sea cucumbers, sponges, turret shell, cushion star, spotty, sea urchin
General Public Description: Blue cod and spotty fish swim above a seafloor with roaming holothurians (sea cucumbers). A cushion star is also discernible. Turret shells, filtering sponges and sea urchins also stand out.

Description: Spotty, urchins, horse mussel, sponges, sea cucumber, eleven arm starfish,
General Public Description: A spotty fish briefly crosses the camera. Horse mussels and sponges protrude from the floor, and create three dimensional habitat structure for other animals. Eleven-armed starfish, sea urchins and sea cucumbers dwell amongst them.

Description: Eleven arm star fish, urchins, sea cumcumber, blue cod, spotty, horse mussel, leather jacket, tube worm structure
General Public Description: Eleven-armed starfish, sea urchins and sea cucumbers slowly move below blue cod and spotty fish. Tube worms filter water, building a protruding structure above the sediment surface. A curious leather jacket investigates the camera weight.  Horse mussels are visible in the murky water.

Description: Horse mussel, tube worms, sea cucumbers, sponges
General Public Description: A filtering horse mussel closes its valves together as it senses movement. Horse mussels can provide a surface or shelter for other organisms, such as tube building worms and sponges. Sea cucumbers can feed on sand, ingesting it to extract nutrients as it ploughs forward. Sponges can also be seen.

Description: Urchins, rocky reef, encrusting sponges, sponges, leather jacket, spotty, tunicates, cushion stars, tube worms, eleven arm starfish, horse mussel
General Public Description: A leatherjacket and spotty fish swim above a rocky reef studed with spiky sea urchins. A cushion star and sea squirts (filter feeding animals) dot the surface of the reef. An eleven-armed starfish, a protruding sea sponge, tube worms, and a horse mussel are also present.

Description: Urchins, encrusting sponges, tube worms, tunicates, horse mussel, eleven arm starfish, fish, sponges, cushion star
General Public Description: A living rocky reef dotted with sea urchins. Sponges (yellow) encrust the rock. Next to the encrusting sponges are tube worms and sea squirts. A fish dashes by in the background. An eleven-armed starfish is just visible. A cusion starfish clings to a horse mussel valve.

Description: Tunicates, tube worms, sponges, sea cucumbers, spotty, eleven arm starfish, horse mussel
General Public Description: Sea squirts are filter feeding animals. Other animals present here include sea cucumbers and sponges. A spotty fish swims by. An eleven-armed starfish is also present (of the genus Coscinasterias). Tube worms and horse mussels protrude from the seafloor. In great numbers they can influence the flow of water over the seafloor.

Description: Horse mussel, eleven arm starfish, tunicates, sea cucumbers
General Public Description: Horse mussel shells provide a substrate upon which other animals can cling to. The faint shape of an eleven-armed starfish is visible. Sea cucumbers traverse the seafloor and sea squirts filter the water.

Description: Cushion stars, sponges, burrows, tracks, microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)s
General Public Description: Cushion stars and sponges are part of the epifauna (animals that live on the seafloor). Across microphytobenthos (microscopic algae)ts, tracks of animals are visible. Burrows hint at the activity of infauna (animals living in the seafloor).

Description: Fish, sea cucumbers, leather jacket, tufts of algae, tube worms, sponges, tarakihi, eleven arm star fish, corraline algae
General Public Description: Leatherjacket and tarakihi fish swim about. Among tufts of algae, sea cucumbers roam. On a rocky reef, white tube worms stand out. An eleven-armed starfish clings to the rocks. Coralline algae paint a rock in pink hues, and tube worms and a sea squirt can be seen here.

Description: Horse mussels, scallops, sponges, tube worms, sea cucumbers, eleven arm star fish, spotty, fish, tunicates
General Public Description: Horse mussels and scallops scattered on the seafloor filter the water. They also undertake ecosystem functions like carbon sequestration and nutrient recycling as they grow and build their shells. Other filterers present here are sea squirts and sponges (though some sponges can be classified as carnivores). Tube worms, sea cucumbers and an eleven-armed starfish can also be seen. Spotty fish swim about.

Description: Urchin barren with sea cucumbers and high sediment cover
General Public Description: Here is an urchin barren with high sediment cover. Sea cucumbers and a brittle star stand out.

Description: Shallow urchin barren with sea cucumbes and high sediment cover
General Public Description: Shallow rubble with sediment cover is dotted with sea urchins, starfishs, algae and sea cucumbers.

Description: Barren with few urchins and high sediment cover
General Public Description: This rocky bottom habitat is barren with high sediment cover and a few sea urchins. Sediments can originate from land-based activities.

A beautiful Carpophyllum flexuosum (macroalgae) forest. Growth of these algae provide important functions like primary production (producing food using the sun's light) and habitat formation for marine invertebrates and fish.
A few sea urchins dot boulders in this barren.
An urchin barren lacking the forest-like cover of large seaweeds.
This image shows an urchin barren with seasonal algae.
An urchin barren with the introduced seaweed Undaria is pictured here.

A close up the kelp Macrocystis, with small air bags at the base of the blades. At the top right corner is the brown seaweed Carpophyllum flexuosum. Kelp forests can be impacted by many factors that can interact, such as overgrazing by urchins and rising sea temperatures.
An urchin barren with sea urchins, sea cucumbers and tube worms.
An urchin barren, with no large brown seaweeds. Many environmental factors can impact the presence and absence of macroalgae.
This rocky bottom is covered in sand and rubble particles. Sea cucumbers are visible.

Description: Deep reef with Galeothrix and high sedimend cover
General Public Description: A biogenic reef with Galeolaria tube worms. This reef has a high sediment cover.

Description: Carpophyllum mashlocarpum fringe reef and urchin barren
General Public Description: A reef fringed with the brown seaweed Carpophyllum maschalocarpum. An urchin barren is also apparent.
A lush clump of the brown seaweed Carpophyllum maschalocarpum. Seaweed growth not only underpins the function of habitat diversity but also functions like nutrient recycling and decomposition.
Urchins creep over the rocks in this barren, caused possibly by their overgrazing on seaweed. Seasonal algae provide sparse cover.
Carpophyllum flexuosum, a brown seaweed, covering the rocks.
Sea urchins (echinoderms) stand out on the bare rocks in this urchin barren.
Within an Ecklonia radiata, kelp, forest, a starfish is visible.
The brown seaweed Carpophyllum flexuosum covers the rocks (left). Ecklonia radiata grows next to it (right and top left).
Lush clumps of the brown seaweeds Carpophyllum flexuosum and Ecklonia radiata sway with the tide. Seaweeds contribute to marine primary production as they photosynthesise.
An Ecklonia radiata forest provides a safe hiding place for marine life.
An urchin barren reveals bare rocks and members of echinodermata (starfishs and sea urchins).

The blades of the brown seaweeds, Carpophyllum maschalocarpum and Lessonia variegata (fettuccine-like), lushly cover rocks. They are an important part of the biodiversity found in rocky reef habitats.
Ecklonia radiata and Lessonia variegata algae blades.
Carpophyllum flexuosum (centre and bush-like) and Ecklonia radiata sway with the tide. Macroalgae such as these support fish populations.
The snake-like arms of a brittle star stand out amongst the blades of the native green algae, Caulerpa brownii.
An Ecklonia radiata forest. Many stressors threaten forests such as these, including threats from land-based activities.
An Ecklonia radiata and Lessonia variegata forest. These brown macroalgae are a considerable source of organic matter that fuels coastal marine foodwebs.
A Carpophyllum flexuosum (left) and Ecklonia radiata (right) forest cover rocks and provide shelter for marine creatures.
Urchin barrens dotted with many sea urchins and sea cucumbers.
An urchin barren.
An urchin barren may be caused by factors such as land-based activities and targeted fishing of predators that eat and control urchin populations.
An urchin barren dotted with many sea urchins.
A patchy forest of the seaweed Undaria.
A rocky reef with Undaria and Carpophyllum flexuosum seaweed.
An underwater forest.  These are important to protect and connect to other forests for ecological function now and in the future.
A Carpophyllum flexuosum forest on cobble stones.
An urchin barren. This barren is bare of habitat structuring macroalgae, whose functions contribute to several ecosystem services, including food production.
A patch of Carpophyllum flexuosum seaweed cover some cobbles.

Description: Sand and gravel wiht urchins and drift algae
General Public Description: A seafloor composed of sand and gravel. Urchins and drifting algae are visible.
An urchin barren. Predators of sea urchins include the heavily fished species blue cod and rock lobsters.

Description: Undaria forest with high sediment cover
General Public Description: An Undaria seaweed forest powdered with a high sediment load, an ecological stressor. A high sedimentation load can be the result of landbased activities.
A rocky bottom is bare of seaweeds and barren from the activity of sea urchins.
An underwater forest composed of the brown seaweed Undaria.
A rocky reef in an urchin barren state. The tubes of tube worms are visible on the right, creating biogenic structure on the reef.

Description: Mixed algae on cobbles and gravel
General Public Description: A rocky seafloor bottom composed of cobble and gravel partly covered by a mixed algae community. The biodiversity that underpins ecosystem function is not only composed of animals but importantly also photosynthesising organisms like algae.
Urchins dot a seafloor clothed in seasonal algae.

Description: Undaria, seasonal algae and urchin barren
General Public Description: A patch of seasonal algae and Undaria kelp stand out amongst the bare rocks of an urchin barren.

Description: Mixed substrate barren with high sediment cover
General Public Description: A rocky barren with high sediment cover. Barren habitats lack the cover of ecologically significant algae, like brown seaweeds, that play an important role in marine productivity.
In this urchin barren, sea cucumbers and sea urchins clearly stand out against the rocks.
This fringe reef is clothed in the brown seaweed Carpophyllum flexuosum.

Description: Cobbles and gravel with high sediment cover
General Public Description: Gravel and cobbles are covered with sediment.
A Carpophyllum flexuosum forest covers this rocky seafloor.
Urchins creep amongst a Carpophyllum flexuosum forest.
A few patches of Undaria seaweed stick out in this urchin barren. Urchins graze on algae like brown seaweeds.
An urchin barren with patches of the seaweed Undaria provides little seafloor cover.

Description: Barren reef with high sand cover
General Public Description: This  reef has a high sand cover and is in a barren state, with no marcoalgae (large seaweed) cover.
A close up of an Undaria forest. Thick patches of brown seaweeds such as this one is a source of organic matter that can entre the foodweb of the Sounds, traveling through the food chain.
This rocky bottom is in a barren state. Spiky sea urchins dot the seafloor.

Description: Mixed weed fringe reef with Undaria
General Public Description: A fringe reef is covered with Undaria and other seaweeds.
The tube worms, Galeolaria hystrix, secrete tubes as homes and capture food particles in the water. They stand out in this urchin barren, providing habitat for other species in the reef.

Description: Urchin barren with patches of Undaria
General Public Description: Patches of the seaweed Undaria contrast against the surrounding bare rock in this urchin barren.
An urchin barren lacking the cover of brown macroalgae (large seaweeds).

Tube worms Galeolaria hystrix are habitat structuring animals. Their growth can influence the flow of water over the seabed and provide habitat for other animals. Patches of Galeolaria stand out in this urchin barren.
This seafloor is composed of sand and gravel.
A patch of Undaria seaweed stands among dozens of grazing sea urchins.

Description: Unconsolidated substrate and seasonal drift algae
General Public Description: Seasonal drift algae covers the seafloor composed of unconsolidated substrate (small loose particles)
Echinodermata (starfish, sea urchins and sea cucumbers) stand out clearly on the boulders of this urchin barren.

Dozens of sea urchins sit on the bare rocks of this urchin barren. Predators of sea urchins here include blue cod and rock lobsters. Fishing activity can have a profound effect on marine population dynamics.
A close up of a native Macrocystis pyrifera kelp blade. Kelps like Macrocystis in rocky marine seafloors are important habitat forming species, forming underwater forests.
The brown seaweed Carpophyllum flexuosum and the kelp Ecklonia radiata are an important part of the biodiversity in rocky bottom marine habitats.
An urchin barren with a lot of sediment.
Native Ecklonia radiata kelp covers the rocks. Photosynthesis under the water produces organic matter that can enter the coastal marine food web.
The native kelp Macrocystis pyrifera and the invasive kelp Undaria pinnatifida are visible here.
The camera blurs past a Carpophyllum flexuosum seaweed forest.

Description: Urchin barren with high sediment cover
General Public Description: Echinodermata (sea urchins and sea cucumbers) are clearly visible in this urchin barren with a high sediment cover.
This seafloor is composed of bare boulders and cobbles.
Light hits the bottom of this seafloor carpeted with the native green seaweed Caulerpa brownii.
A barren seafloor with some drift algae. Blue cod, starfish and a sea cucumber are visible.
An urchin barren such as the one pictured here may be caused by the decline in urchin predators due to fishing.
An Ecklonia radiata kelp forest with some Marginariella brown seaweed provides a hiding place for fish and invertebrates.
Carpophyllum flexuosum and Ecklonia radiata cover the rocks with their blades (the equivalent to leaves on a plant).
An urchin barren reveals the presense of the ecosystem engineer Galeolaria hystrix, a tube-building polychaete worm.
An urchin barren with no large brown seaweeds to provide cover.
A reef deep in the water is dominated by the presence of invertebrates, including starfish and sea cucumbers.
Fringe habitat composed of the brown seaweed Carpophyllum maschalocarpum.

Description: Shallow mash fringe descending to urchin barren and deeper unconsolidated seafloor.
General Public Description: On the left in shallow waters, Carpophyllum maschalocarpum makes food for itself using the energy of the sun. Descending, signs of urchin barren are apparent. The seafloor at the bottom is composed of loose, small substrate.
Sea cucumbers and urchins stand out starkly in this barren. Overgrazing by urchins may be one cause of the disapearance of large brown seaweeds.
An urchin barren lacking the forest-like cover of large attached macroalgae (seaweed). Seasonal algae is visible.
Urchin barrens such as this one pictured may be termed alternative states, compared to large brown seaweed forests that contain more biodiversity.

Description: Carpophyllum mash fringe and Ecklonia below
General Public Description: Beautiful Carpophyllum maschalocarpum fringe habitat (at the forefront in this image) with Ecklonia radiata further back.
